:"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from any of several places called Halton in Cheshire, Lancashire, Yorkshire, Northumberland, Lincolnshire, Shropshire and Buckinghamshire. Halton is usually from Old English <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, hollow’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. Halton in Cheshire, however, is possibly named from an Old English <i>hāthel</i> ‘heathery place’ + <i>tūn</i>, and Halton in Northumberland from an Old English <i>hāw</i> ‘look out’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish: variant of   Holton  .","History: Most English bearers of this name trace their descent from William de Halton, who was living at Halton, Lancashire, in 1346."],"variants":[{"name":"Holton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Holton, such as those in Oxfordshire, Suffolk, Dorset, and Somerset. The Oxfordshire and Somerset placenames derive from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Suffolk placename comes from the Old English personal name <i>Hōla</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Dorset placename derives from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ or <i>holt</i> ‘wood, grove, thicket’ + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish: altered form of <b>O'Haltahan</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hUltacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ultachán</i>’, a diminutive of <i>Ultach</i> ‘Ulsterman’. This is a rare Fermanagh surname, sometimes Anglicized as   Nolan  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":69,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Ralph de Halton was born about 1190, in Devon, England. He had at least 1 son with Joan."},"et":{"about 1190–":"umbes 1190–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1224":"1224","1220":"1220","1195":"1195","about 1220":"umbes 1220","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1190–":"noin 1190–Kuollut","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1190":"noin 1190","122